mm: restore mmap_lock count/owner cacheline split in mm_struct

Commit 2e3025434a6b ("mm: relocate 'write_protect_seq' in struct
mm_struct") deliberately placed mmap_lock at offset 56 from a cacheline
boundary so that its two hot fields 'count' and 'owner' sit in two
different cachelines, quoting Linus' analysis of why that layout is
optimal under contention (new waiters cmpxchg 'count' on the first
line, spinners poll 'owner' on the second). Breaking that split was
measured back then as a 9.2% will-it-scale regression, and the comment
above mmap_lock (refreshed by commit 61dc4358d37a ("mm: correct
misleading comment on mmap_lock field in mm_struct")) explicitly warns:
"please be careful with adding new fields before mmap_lock".

Commit 8cea569ca785 ("sched/mmcid: Use proper data structures")
inserted the 192-byte cacheline-aligned mm_cid struct before mmap_lock,
and the sched_cache statistics later added another aligned 64 bytes.
On x86-64 with SCHED_MM_CID=y mmap_lock now sits at offset 16 from the
cacheline boundary: 'count' and 'owner' share one line, together with
pgtables_bytes and page_table_lock, which other CPUs write from
page-table allocation and teardown paths. The 64-byte alignment of
mm_cid also left a dead 56-byte hole after mm_users.

Restore the documented layout:

  - Move pgtables_bytes, map_count, page_table_lock and mmlist into
    the hole after mm_users, shrinking it from 56 to 24 bytes and
    taking those write paths off mmap_lock's line. This does put them
    on the same line as membarrier_state (read by switch_mm()) and
    mm_users; that is strictly better than sharing with mmap_lock's
    'count' as they do today, page_table_lock is cold with split
    ptlocks (only pud/pmd-level table allocation), and pgtables_bytes
    writes are once-per-PTE-table plus a burst in free_pgtables() --
    [context-switch benchmark placeholder to confirm no regression].

  - Move the seven VM counters (hiwater_rss through exec_vm, 56 bytes
    on 64-bit) directly before mmap_lock, with a cacheline alignment
    anchor on hiwater_rss. They are written under mmap_lock write or
    from low-rate paths (update_hiwater_rss() from reclaim/migration,
    pinned_vm accounting from pin/unpin), so 'count' shares its line
    with nothing that other CPUs access at high frequency, and 'owner'
    starts the following line again.

The anchor makes the offset independent of the config-dependent fields
above it (mm_cid and sc_stat both collapse to empty unaligned structs
when their configs are off, so the offset previously depended on
config); it costs no space when either of those aligned structs is
present, and at most 24 bytes of padding otherwise.

pahole on x86-64 (SCHED_MM_CID=y, SCHED_CACHE=y, PER_VMA_LOCK=y):

  before: mmap_lock at 464 (offset 16), count+owner same line,
          sharing with page_table_lock/pgtables_bytes;
          56-byte hole at 136; size 1728, 27 cachelines
  after:  mmap_lock at 504 (offset 56), count last word of its line,
          owner opening the next; size 1664, 26 cachelines

PER_VMA_LOCK fields sit after mmap_lock, so its offset is unaffected
by that config; with !CONFIG_MMU, pgtables_bytes vanishes but the
anchor keeps the offset at 56.

[benchmark results placeholder - will-it-scale mmap1/page_fault
 threads interleaved A/B + context-switch-heavy benchmark, in flight]

Fixes: 8cea569ca785 ("sched/mmcid: Use proper data structures")
